		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Pottsville</placeName> <date>October 7<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1851</date></p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">Rev. &#38; Dear Sir&#44;</p>
          <p rend="indent(3)">Although an entire stranger to you&#44;<lb/> I hope you will excuse the liberty I now take in addres<lb/>sing you. &#160;&#160;You are known to me by reputation&#44; as<lb/> one thoroughly learned in ancient as well as modern<lb/> Hebrew lore&#59; and as possessing a <add>&#63;</add> of information<lb/> on general matters connected with the history of<lb/> your race&#44; rarely to be found. And I hope that my<lb/> earnest desire to attain the knowledge of the truth<lb/> will be a sufficient apology for my addressing you this<lb/> letter. &#160;&#160;My object in writing you&#44; is&#44; to ob<lb/>tain for my own individual benefit&#44; some information<lb/> in regard to the practice of the Israelites in the cele&#45;<lb/>bration of the <date>Passover</date> about the time of the birth of<lb/> <persName>Christ</persName>. And that you may readily apprehend what<lb/> I want to be at&#44; I will reduce it to the form of a<lb/> question. What was the subject matter of praise<lb/> at the conclusion of the <date>Passover</date> service&#63; Was it<lb/> <hi rend="underline">the Hallel</hi> embracing Psalms 113&#45;117&#63; or was it a<lb/> Hymn composed in honor of the expected Messiah&#63;</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">The church with which I am connected uses<lb/> exclusively the Psalms of David&#44; rendered into rueter<add>&#63;</add>&#44;<lb/> in the worship of God&#58; and her reason for so doing&#44; is<lb/> the example of the founder of the Christian religion.</p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p>who in conformity with Jewish custom&#44; celebrated his<lb/> last <date>Passover</date> by using the <hi rend="underline">Hallel</hi> referred to&#44; intimating<lb/> thereby&#44; that he would have his disciples use the Psalms<lb/> of David exclusively in the worship of God to the end<lb/> of the world. &#40;This is not the only reason for our prac&#45;<lb/>tice&#44; but it is one of the principal ones.&#41;</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I have recently heard it objected&#44; that <persName>Christ</persName> did not<lb/> use the <hi rend="underline">Hallel</hi> in the instance referred to&#44; for it was<lb/> not the custom of the Jews to use it on such an occas<lb/>sion&#44; but to sing a Hymn in honor of the expected<lb/> Messiah&#8212;the same Hymn now contained in the<lb/> &#8220;<hi rend="underline">Hagada al Passah</hi>&#44;&#8221; and still sung at the conclusion<lb/> of that service. &#160;&#160;If such a Hymn was used<lb/> at the time referred to&#44; and is now contained in the<lb/> &#8220;Hagada&#8221; and is still used&#58; be so kind as to give me<lb/> its history&#8212;when it first began to be used&#44; and by<lb/> whom composed&#58; and also where I can obtain a copy<lb/> of the &#8220;Hagada&#8221; in Hebrew and English.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I write this in all candor and honesty&#44; and sincerely desire<lb/> that you will favor me with an answer and throw some<lb/> light on a subject&#44; in regard to which I have seen nothing<lb/> yet satisfactory. &#160;&#160;</p> 
          <p rend="indent(1)">With great regard</p>
          <p rend="indent(2)">Yours very sincerely</p>
          <p rend="indent(3)"><persName role="author">D. T. Carnahan</persName></p>
          
        </body>
